## What is hub and spoke model


The Hub-and-Spoke model is a network architecture where one central network (the hub) connects to multiple other networks (the spokes). Instead of every network connecting directly to every other network, all communication goes through the hub.

Simple diagram
          VPC-1 (Spoke)
               |
               |
VPC-2 ---- Hub (Transit Gateway) ---- VPC-3
               |
               |
          VPC-4 (Spoke)
Hub = Central network device (often a AWS Transit Gateway in AWS).
Spokes = Individual VPCs connected to the hub.
Example in AWS

Suppose you have:

VPC-A → VPN Server
VPC-B → Application Server
VPC-C → Database Server

Instead of creating separate peering connections:

VPC-A ↔ VPC-B
VPC-A ↔ VPC-C
VPC-B ↔ VPC-C

You attach all three VPCs to a single Transit Gateway:

          VPC-A
            |
            |
     Transit Gateway
       /           \
   VPC-B         VPC-C

Now:

VPC-A can reach VPC-B.
VPC-A can reach VPC-C.
VPC-B can reach VPC-C.

You manage routing in one place instead of many.

Why use the Hub-and-Spoke model?
Simpler management – one central hub manages connectivity.
Scalable – adding a new VPC only requires attaching it to the hub.
Centralized security – firewalls, VPNs, or inspection services can be placed at the hub.
Lower operational complexity than creating many VPC peering connections.
